There’s a strategic principle in what you’re describing that I think is worth separating from the metaphor.

Flanking works because you’re not trying to overpower the strongest part of a system. You’re looking for places where the system is underserved, fragmented, or neglected. In business, those are often where the best opportunities are.

Some recurring “cracks in the armor” are:

* Handoffs. Every time work passes between teams, companies, or software, information gets lost.
* Context switching. People pay a hidden tax every time they have to reconstruct what was happening.
* One-off decisions. Companies make expensive decisions repeatedly without preserving why they made them.
* Small markets ignored by incumbents. A niche that is too small for a large company can be an excellent business for a focused one.
* Coordination problems. When multiple people know pieces of the answer but no one sees the whole picture.

Those margins are often easier to enter than competing head-on with established players.

