Your AI thought is interesting, and I think it becomes stronger with one shift.

Instead of each company having “its own chatbot,” imagine each company having its own evolving organizational model.

Not just a document repository.

A living representation of:

* how work actually flows,
* which teams communicate,
* where decisions originate,
* recurring bottlenecks,
* institutional memory,
* confidence and uncertainty around different areas.

Employees wouldn’t simply ask, “Where is the policy?”

They could ask:

* “If we change this process, who is likely to be affected?”
* “Why did we stop doing this three years ago?”
* “Who inside the company has solved something similar?”
* “Which assumptions does this proposal depend on?”

That starts to resemble a digital organizational twin rather than just an AI assistant.

The key isn’t that it knows facts.

It’s that it understands relationships.

